 [66] "we keep stored away somewhere all our memories, the good as well as the"                 
 [67] "evil, the pleasant together with the unpleasant. There may be nightmares"                
 [68] "down cellar, as we thought as a child, but even in those days we knew"                   
 [69] "how to dodge them when we went after apples; that is, take down a light"                 
 [70] "and slam the door quickly on coming up."                                                 
 [71] ""                                                                                        
 [72] "Maeterlinck, too, knew this trick of our childhood. When in the Palace"                  
 [73] "of Night scene of his fairy play, the redoubtable Tyltyl unlocks the"                    
 [74] "cage where are confined the nightmares and all other evil imaginings, he"                
 [75] "shuts the door in time to keep them in and then opens another revealing"                 
 [76] "a lovely garden full of blue birds, which, though they fade and die when"                
 [77] "brought into the light of common day, yet encourage him to continue his"                 
 [78] "search for the Blue Bird that never fades, but lives everlastingly. The"                 
 [79] "new science of dreams is giving a deeper significance to the trite wish"                 
 [80] "of \\\"Good night and pleasant dreams!\\\" It means sweet sanity and mental"             
 [81] "health, pure thoughts and good will to all men."                                         
 [82] ""                                                                                        
 [83] "Professor Bergson\\'s theory of dreaming here set forth in untechnical"                  
 [84] "language, fits into a particular niche in his general system of"                         
 [85] "philosophy as well as does his little book on _Laughter_. With the main"                 
 [86] "features of his philosophy the English-reading public is better"                         
 [87] "acquainted than with any other contemporary system, for his books have"                  
 [88] "sold even more rapidly here than in France. When Professor Bergson"                      
 [89] "visited the United States two years ago the lecture-rooms of Columbia"                   
 [90] "University, like those of the Coll\\u00e8ge de France, were packed to the"               
 [91] "doors and the effect of his message was enhanced by his eloquence of"                    
 [92] "delivery and charm of personality. The pragmatic character of his"                       
 [93] "philosophy appeals to the genius of the American people as is shown by"                  
 [94] "the influence of the teaching of William James and John Dewey, whose"                    
 [95] "point of view in this respect resembles Bergson\\'s."                                    
 [96] ""                                                                                        
 [97] "During the present generation chemistry and biology have passed from the"                
 [98] "descriptive to the creative stage. Man is becoming the overlord of the"                  
 [99] "mineral, vegetable and animal kingdoms. He is learning to make gems and"                 
[100] "perfumes, drugs and foods, to suit his tastes, instead of depending upon"                
[101] "the chance bounty of nature. He is beginning consciously to adapt means"                 
[102] "to ends and to plan for the future even in the field of politics. He has"                
[103] "opened up the atom and finds in it a microcosm more complex than the"                    
[104] "solar system. He beholds the elements melting with fervent heat and he"                  
[105] "turns their rays to the healing of his sores. He drives the lightning"                   
[106] "through the air and with the product feeds his crops. He makes the"                      
[107] "desert to blossom as the rose and out of the sea he draws forth dry"                     
[108] "land. He treats the earth as his habitation, remodeling it in accordance"                
[109] "with his ever-varying needs and increasing ambitions."                                   
[110] ""                                                                                        
[111] "This modern man, planning, contriving and making, finds Paley\\'s watch as"              
[112] "little to his mind as Lucretius\\'s blind flow of atoms. A universe wound"               
[113] "up once for all and doing nothing thereafter but mark time is as"                        
[114] "incomprehensible to him as a universe that never had a mind of its own"                  
[115] "and knows no difference between past and future. The idea of eternal"                    
[116] "recurrence does not frighten him as it did Nietzsche, for he feels it to"                
[117] "be impossible. The mechanistic interpretation of natural phenomena"                      
[118] "developed during the last century he accepts at its full value, and"                     
[119] "would extend experimentally as far as it will go, for he finds it not"                   
[120] "invalid but inadequate."                                                                 
[121] ""                                                                                        
[122] "To minds of this temperament it is no wonder that Bergson\\'s _Creative"                 
[123] "Evolution_ came with the force of an inspiration. Men felt themselves"                   
[124] "akin to this upward impulse, this _\\u00e9lan vital_, which, struggling"                 
[125] "throughout the ages with the intractableness of inert matter, yet"                       
[126] "finally in some way or other forces it to its will, and ever strives"                    
[127] "toward the increase of vitality, mentality, personality."                                
[128] ""                                                                                        
[129] "Bergson has been reluctant to commit himself on the question of"                         
[130] "immortality, but he of late has become quite convinced of it. He even"                   
[131] "goes so far as to think it possible that we may find experimental"                       
[132] "evidence of personal persistence after death. This at least we might"                    
[133] "infer from his recent acceptance of the presidency of the British"                       
[134] "Society for Psychical Research. In his opening address before the"                       
[135] "Society, May 28, 1913, he discussed the question of telepathy and in"                    
[136] "that connection he explained his theory of the relation of mind and"                     
[137] "brain in the following language. I quote from the report in the London"                  
[138] "_Times_:"                                                                                
[139] ""                                                                                        
[140] ""                                                                                        
[141] "     The _r\\u00f4le_ of the brain is to bring back the remembrance of an"               
[142] "     action, to prolong the remembrance in movements. If one could see"                  
[143] "     all that takes place in the interior of the brain, one would find"                  
[144] "     that that which takes place there corresponds to a small part only"                 
[145] "     of the life of the mind. The brain simply extracts from the life of"                
[146] "     the mind that which is capable of representation in movement. The"                  
[147] "     cerebral life is to the mental life what the movements of the baton"                
[148] "     of a conductor are to the Symphony."                                                
[149] ""                                                                                        
[150] "     The brain, then, is that which allows the mind to adjust itself"                    
[151] "     exactly to circumstances. It is the organ of attention to life."                    
[152] "     Should it become deranged, however slightly, the mind is no longer"                 
[153] "     fitted to the circumstances; it wanders, dreams. Many forms of"                     
[154] "     mental alienation are nothing else. But from this it results that"                  
[155] "     one of the _r\\u00f4les_ of the brain is to limit the vision of the"                
[156] "     mind, to render its action more efficacious. This is what we"                       
[157] "     observe in regard to the memory, where the _r\\u00f4le_ of the brain is"            
[158] "     to mask the useless part of our past in order to allow only the"                    
[159] "     useful remembrances to appear. Certain useless recollections, or"                   
[160] "     dream remembrances, manage nevertheless to appear also, and to form"                
[161] "     a vague fringe around the distinct recollections. It would not be"                  
[162] "     at all surprising if perceptions of the organs of our senses,"                      
[163] "     useful perceptions, were the result of a selection or of a"                         
[164] "     canalization worked by the organs of our senses in the interest of"                 
[165] "     our action, but that there should yet be around those perceptions a"                
[166] "     fringe of vague perceptions, capable of becoming more distinct in"                  
[167] "     extraordinary, abnormal cases. Those would be precisely the cases"                  
[168] "     with which psychical research would deal."                                          
[169] ""                                                                                        
[170] ""                                                                                        
[171] "This conception of mental action forms, as will be seen, the foundation"                 
[172] "of the theory of dreams which Professor Bergson first presented in a"                    
[173] "lecture before the _Institut psychologique_, March 26, 1901. It was"                     
[174] "published in the _Revue scientifique_ of June 8, 1901. An English"                       
[175] "translation, revised by the author and printed in _The Independent_ of"                  
[176] "October 23 and 30, 1913, here appears for the first time in book form."                  
[177] ""                                                                                        
[178] "In this essay Professor Bergson made several contributions to our"                       
[179] "knowledge of dreams. He showed, in the first place, that dreaming is not"                
[180] "so unlike the ordinary process of perception as had been hitherto"                       
[181] "supposed. Both use sense impressions as crude material to be molded and"                 
[182] "defined by the aid of memory images. Here, too, he set forth the idea,"                  
[183] "which he, so far as I know, was the first to formulate, that sleep is a"                 
[184] "state of disinterestedness, a theory which has since been adopted by"                    
[185] "several psychologists. In this address, also, was brought into"                          
[186] "consideration for the first time the idea that the self may go through"                  
[187] "different degrees of tension--a theory referred to in his _Matter and"                   
[188] "Memory_."                                                                                
[189] ""                                                                                        
[190] "Its chief interest for the general reader will, however, lie in the"                     
[191] "explanation it gives him of the cause of some of his familiar dreams. He"                
[192] "may by practice become the interpreter of his own visions and so come to"                
[193] "an understanding of the vagaries of that mysterious and inseparable"                     
[194] "companion, his dream-self."                                                              
[195] ""                                                                                        
[196] ""                                                                                        
[197] "                                            EDWIN E. SLOSSON."                           
[198] ""                                                                                        
[199] "  NEW YORK CITY,"                                                                        
[200] "  FEBRUARY 10, 1914."                                                                    
[201] ""                                                                                        
[202] ""                                                                                        
[203] ""                                                                                        
[204] ""                                                                                        
[205] "DREAMS"                                                                                  
[206] ""                                                                                        
[207] ""                                                                                        
[208] "The subject which I have to discuss here is so complex, it raises so"                    
[209] "many questions of all kinds, difficult, obscure, some psychological,"                    
[210] "others physiological and metaphysical; in order to be treated in a"                      
[211] "complete manner it requires such a long development--and we have so"                     
[212] "little space, that I shall ask your permission to dispense with all"                     
[213] "preamble, to set aside unessentials, and to go at once to the heart of"                  
[214] "the question."                                                                           
[215] ""                                                                                        
[216] "A dream is this. I perceive objects and there is nothing there. I see"                   
[217] "men; I seem to speak to them and I hear what they answer; there is no"                   
[218] "one there and I have not spoken. It is all _as if_ real things and real"                 
[219] "persons were there, then on waking all has disappeared, both persons and"                
[220] "things. How does this happen?"                                                           
[221] ""                                                                                        
[222] "But, first, is it true that there is nothing there? I mean, is there not"                
[223] "presented a certain sense material to our eyes, to our ears, to our"                     
[224] "touch, etc., during sleep as well as during waking?"                                     
[225] ""                                                                                        
[226] "Close the eyes and look attentively at what goes on in the field of our"                 
[227] "vision. Many persons questioned on this point would say that nothing"                    
[228] "goes on, that they see nothing. No wonder at this, for a certain amount"                 
[229] "of practise is necessary to be able to observe oneself satisfactorily."                  
[230] "But just give the requisite effort of attention, and you will"                           
[231] "distinguish, little by little, many things. First, in general, a black"                  
[232] "background. Upon this black background occasionally brilliant points"                    
[233] "which come and go, rising and descending, slowly and sedately. More"                     
[234] "often, spots of many colors, sometimes very dull, sometimes, on the"                     
[235] "contrary, with certain people, so brilliant that reality cannot compare"                 
[236] "with it. These spots spread and shrink, changing form and color,"                        
[237] "constantly displacing one another. Sometimes the change is slow and"                     
[238] "gradual, sometimes again it is a whirlwind of vertiginous rapidity."                     
[239] "Whence comes all this phantasmagoria? The physiologists and the"                         
[240] "psychologists have studied this play of colors. \\\"Ocular spectra,\\\""                 
[241] "\\\"colored spots,\\\" \\\"phosphenes,\\\" such are the names that they have given"      
[242] "to the phenomenon. They explain it either by the slight modifications"                   
[243] "which occur ceaselessly in the retinal circulation, or by the pressure"                  
[244] "that the closed lid exerts upon the eyeball, causing a mechanical"                       
[245] "excitation of the optic nerve. But the explanation of the phenomenon and"                
[246] "the name that is given to it matters little. It occurs universally and"                  
[247] "it constitutes--I may say at once--the principal material of which we"                   
[248] "shape our dreams, \\\"such stuff as dreams are made on.\\\""                             
[249] ""                                                                                        
[250] "Thirty or forty years ago, M. Alfred Maury and, about the same time, M."                 
[251] "d\\'Hervey, of St. Denis, had observed that at the moment of falling"                    
[252] "asleep these colored spots and moving forms consolidate, fix themselves,"                
[253] "take on definite outlines, the outlines of the objects and of the"                       
[254] "persons which people our dreams. But this is an observation to be"                       
[255] "accepted with caution, since it emanates from psychologists already half"                
[256] "asleep. More recently an American psychologist, Professor Ladd, of"                      
[257] "Yale, has devised a more rigorous method, but of difficult application,"                 
[258] "because it requires a sort of training. It consists in acquiring the"                    
[259] "habit on awakening in the morning of keeping the eyes closed and"                        
[260] "retaining for some minutes the dream that is fading from the field of"                   
[261] "vision and soon would doubtless have faded from that of memory. Then one"                
[262] "sees the figures and objects of the dream melt away little by little"                    
[263] "into phosphenes, identifying themselves with the colored spots that the"                 
[264] "eye really perceives when the lids are closed. One reads, for example, a"                
[265] "newspaper; that is the dream. One awakens and there remains of the"                      
[266] "newspaper, whose definite outlines are erased, only a white spot with"                   
[267] "black marks here and there; that is the reality. Or our dream takes us"                  
[268] "upon the open sea--round about us the ocean spreads its waves of"                        
[269] "yellowish gray with here and there a crown of white foam. On awakening,"                 
[270] "it is all lost in a great spot, half yellow and half gray, sown with"                    
[271] "brilliant points. The spot was there, the brilliant points were there."                  
[272] "There was really presented to our perceptions, in sleep, a visual dust,"                 
[273] "and it was this dust which served for the fabrication of our dreams."                    
[274] ""                                                                                        
[275] "Will this alone suffice? Still considering the sensation of sight, we"                   
[276] "ought to add to these visual sensations which we may call internal all"                  
[277] "those which continue to come to us from an external source. The eyes,"                   
[278] "when closed, still distinguish light from shade, and even, to a certain"                 
[279] "extent, different lights from one another. These sensations of light,"                   
[280] "emanating from without, are at the bottom of many of our dreams. A"                      
[281] "candle abruptly lighted in the room will, for example, suggest to the"                   
[282] "sleeper, if his slumber is not too deep, a dream dominated by the image"                 
[283] "of fire, the idea of a burning building. Permit me to cite to you two"                   
[284] "observations of M. Tissi\\u00e9 on this subject:"                                        
[285] ""                                                                                        
[286] "\\\"B---- L\\u00e9on dreams that the theater of Alexandria is on _fire_; the"            
[287] "flame lights up the whole place. All of a sudden he finds himself"                       
[288] "transported to the midst of the fountain in the public square; a line"                   
[289] "of _fire_ runs along the chains which connect the great posts placed"                    
[290] "around the margin. Then he finds himself in Paris at the exposition,"                    
[291] "which is on _fire_. He takes part in terrible scenes, etc. He wakes with"                
[292] "a start; his eyes catch the rays of light projected by the dark lantern"                 
[293] "which the night nurse flashes toward his bed in passing. M---- Bertrand"                 
[294] "dreams that he is in the marine infantry where he formerly served. He"                   
[295] "goes to Fort-de-France, to Toulon, to Loriet, to Crimea, to"                             
[296] "Constantinople. He sees lightning, he hears thunder, he takes part in a"                 
[297] "combat in which he sees _fire_ leap from the mouths of cannon. He wakes"                 
[298] "with a start. Like B., he was wakened by a flash of light projected from"                
[299] "the dark lantern of the night nurse.\\\" Such are often the dreams provoked"             
[300] "by a bright and sudden light."                                                           
[301] ""                                                                                        
[302] "Very different are those which are suggested by a mild and continuous"                   
[303] "light like that of the moon. A. Krauss tells how one day on awakening he"                
[304] "perceived that he was extending his arm toward what in his dream"                        
[305] "appeared to him to be the image of a young girl. Little by little this"                  
[306] "image melted into that of the full moon which darted its rays upon him."                 
[307] "It is a curious thing that one might cite other examples of dreams where"                
[308] "the rays of the moon, caressing the eyes of the sleeper, evoked before"                  
[309] "him virginal apparitions. May we not suppose that such might have been"                  
[310] "the origin in antiquity of the fable of Endymion--Endymion the shepherd,"                
[311] "lapped in perpetual slumber, for whom the goddess Selene, that is, the"                  
[312] "moon, is smitten with love while he sleeps?"                                             
[313] ""                                                                                        
[314] "I have spoken of visual sensations. They are the principal ones. But the"                
[315] "auditory sensations nevertheless play a r\\u00f4le. First, the ear has also"             
[316] "its internal sensations, sensations of buzzing, of tinkling, of"                         
[317] "whistling, difficult to isolate and to perceive while awake, but which"                  
[318] "are clearly distinguished in sleep. Besides that we continue, when once"                 
[319] "asleep, to hear external sounds. The creaking of furniture, the"                         
[320] "crackling of the fire, the rain beating against the window, the wind"                    
[321] "playing its chromatic scale in the chimney, such are the sounds which"                   
[322] "come to the ear of the sleeper and which the dream converts, according"                  
[323] "to circumstances, into conversation, singing, cries, music, etc."                        
[324] "Scissors were struck against the tongs in the ears of Alfred Maury while"                
[325] "he slept. Immediately he dreamt that he heard the tocsin and took part"                  
[326] "in the events of June, 1848. Such observations and experiences are"                      
[327] "numerous. But let us hasten to say that sounds do not play in our dreams"                
[328] "so important a r\\u00f4le as colors. Our dreams are, above all, visual, and"             
[329] "even more visual than we think. To whom has it not happened--as M. Max"                  
[330] "Simon has remarked--to talk in a dream with a certain person, to dream a"                
[331] "whole conversation, and then, all of a sudden, a singular phenomenon"                    
[332] "strikes the attention of the dreamer. He perceives that he does not"                     
[333] "speak, that he has not spoken, that his interlocutor has not uttered a"                  
[334] "single word, that it was a simple exchange of thought between them, a"                   
[335] "very clear conversation, in which, nevertheless, nothing has been heard."                
[336] "The phenomenon is easily enough explained. It is in general necessary"                   
[337] "for us to hear sounds in a dream. From nothing we can make nothing. And"                 
[338] "when we are not provided with sonorous material, a dream would find it"                  
[339] "hard to manufacture sonority."                                                           
[340] ""                                                                                        
[341] "There is much more to say about the sensations of touch than about those"                
[342] "of hearing, but I must hasten. We could talk for hours about the"                        
[343] "singular phenomena which result from the confused sensations of touch"                   
[344] "during sleep. These sensations, mingling with the images which occupy"                   
[345] "our visual field, modify them or arrange them in their own way. Often in"                
[346] "the midst of the night the contact of our body with its light clothing"                  
[347] "makes itself felt all at once and reminds us that we are lightly"                        
[348] "clothed. Then, if our dream is at the moment taking us through the"                      
[349] "street, it is in this simple attire that we present ourselves to the"                    
[350] "gaze of the passers-by, without their appearing to be astonished by it."                 
[351] "We are ourselves astonished in the dream, but that never appears to"                     
[352] "astonish other people. I cite this dream because it is frequent. There"                  
[353] "is another which many of us must have experienced. It consists of"                       
[354] "feeling oneself flying through the air or floating in space. Once having"                
[355] "had this dream, one may be quite sure that it will reappear; and every"                  
[356] "time that it recurs the dreamer reasons in this way: \\\"I have had before"              
[357] "now in a dream the illusion of flying or floating, but this time it is"                  
[358] "the real thing. It has certainly proved to me that we may free ourselves"                
[359] "from the law of gravitation.\\\" Now, if you wake abruptly from this dream,"             
[360] "you can analyze it without difficulty, if you undertake it immediately."                 
[361] "You will see that you feel very clearly that your feet are not touching"                 
[362] "the earth. And, nevertheless, not believing yourself asleep, you have"                   
[363] "lost sight of the fact that you are lying down. Therefore, since you are"                
[364] "not lying down and yet your feet do not feel the resistance of the"                      
[365] "ground, the conclusion is natural that you are floating in space. Notice"                
[366] "this also: when levitation accompanies the flight, it is on one side"                    
[367] "only that you make an effort to fly. And if you woke at that moment you"                 
[368] "would find that this side is the one on which you are lying, and that"                   
[369] "the sensation of effort for flight coincides with the real sensation"                    
[370] "given you by the pressure of your body against the bed. This sensation"                  
[371] "of pressure, dissociated from its cause, becomes a pure and simple"                      
[372] "sensation of effort and, joined to the illusion of floating in space, is"                
[373] "sufficient to produce the dream."                                                        
[374] ""                                                                                        
[375] "It is interesting to see that these sensations of pressure, mounting, so"                
[376] "to speak, to the level of our visual field and taking advantage of the"                  
[377] "luminous dust which fills it, effect its transformation into forms and"                  
[378] "colors. M. Max Simon tells of having a strange and somewhat painful"                     
[379] "dream. He dreamt that he was confronted by two piles of golden coins,"                   
[380] "side by side and of unequal height, which for some reason or other he"                   
[381] "had to equalize. But he could not accomplish it. This produced a feeling"                
[382] "of extreme anguish. This feeling, growing moment by moment, finally"                     
[383] "awakened him. He then perceived that one of his legs was caught by the"                  
[384] "folds of the bedclothes in such a way that his two feet were on"                         
[385] "different levels and it was impossible for him to bring them together."                  
[386] "From this the sensation of inequality, making an irruption into the"                     
[387] "visual field and there encountering (such at least is the hypothesis"                    
[388] "which I propose) one or more yellow spots, expressed itself visually by"                 
[389] "the inequality of the two piles of gold pieces. There is, then, immanent"                
[390] "in the tactile sensations during sleep, a tendency to visualize"                         
[391] "themselves and enter in this form into the dream."                                       
[392] ""                                                                                        
[393] "More important still than the tactile sensations, properly speaking, are"                
[394] "the sensations which pertain to what is sometimes called internal touch,"                
[395] "deep-seated sensations emanating from all points of the organism and,"                   
[396] "more particularly, from the viscera. One cannot imagine the degree of"                   
[397] "sharpness, of acuity, which may be obtained during sleep by these"                       
[398] "interior sensations. They doubtless already exist as well during waking."                
[399] "But we are then distracted by practical action. We live outside of"                      
[400] "ourselves. But sleep makes us retire into ourselves. It happens"                         
[401] "frequently that persons subject to laryngitis, amygdalitis, etc., dream"                 
[402] "that they are attacked by their affection and experience a disagreeable"                 
[403] "tingling on the side of their throat. When awakened, they feel nothing"                  
[404] "more, and believe it an illusion; but a few hours later the illusion"                    
[405] "becomes a reality. There are cited maladies and grave accidents, attacks"                
[406] "of epilepsy, cardiac affections, etc., which have been foreseen and, as"                 
[407] "it were, prophesied in dreams. We need not be astonished, then, that"                    
[408] "philosophers like Schopenhauer have seen in the dream a reverberation,"                  
[409] "in the heart of consciousness, of perturbations emanating from the"                      
[410] "sympathetic nervous system; and that psychologists like Schemer have"                    
[411] "attributed to each of our organs the power of provoking a"                               
[412] "well-determined kind of dream which represents it, as it were,"                          
[413] "symbolically; and finally that physicians like Artigues have written"                    
[414] "treatises on the semeiological value of dreams, that is to say, the"                     
[415] "method of making use of dreams for the diagnosis of certain maladies."                   
[416] "More recently, M. Tissi\\u00e9, of whom we have just spoken, has shown how"              
[417] "specific dreams are connected with affections of the digestive,"                         
[418] "respiratory, and circulatory apparatus."                                                 
[419] ""                                                                                        
[420] "I will summarize what I have just been saying. When we are sleeping"                     
[421] "naturally, it is not necessary to believe, as has often been supposed,"                  
[422] "that our senses are closed to external sensations. Our senses continue"                  
[423] "to be active. They act, it is true, with less precision, but in"                         
[424] "compensation they embrace a host of \\\"subjective\\\" impressions which pass"           
[425] "unperceived when we are awake--for then we live in a world of"                           
[426] "perceptions common to all men--and which reappear in sleep, when we live"                
[427] "only for ourselves. Thus our faculty of sense perception, far from being"                
[428] "narrowed during sleep at all points, is on the contrary extended, at"                    
[429] "least in certain directions, in its field of operations. It is true that"                
[430] "it often loses in energy, in _tension_, what it gains in extension. It"                  
[431] "brings to us only confused impressions. These impressions are the"                       
[432] "materials of our dreams. But they are only the materials, they do not"                   
[433] "suffice to produce them."                                                                
[434] ""                                                                                        
[435] "They do not suffice to produce them, because they are vague and"                         
[436] "indeterminate. To speak only of those that play the principal r\\u00f4le, the"           
[437] "changing colors and forms, which deploy before us when our eyes are"                     
[438] "closed, never have well-defined contours. Here are black lines upon a"                   
[439] "white background. They may represent to the dreamer the page of a book,"                 
[440] "or the facade of a new house with dark blinds, or any number of other"                   
[441] "things. Who will choose? What is the form that will imprint its decision"                
[442] "upon the indecision of this material? This form is our memory."                          
[443] ""                                                                                        
[444] "Let us note first that the dream in general creates nothing. Doubtless"                  
[445] "there may be cited some examples of artistic, literary and scientific"                   
[446] "production in dreams. I will recall only the well-known anecdote told of"                
[447] "Tartini, a violinist-composer of the eighteenth century. As he was"                      
[448] "trying to compose a sonata and the muse remained recalcitrant, he went"                  
[449] "to sleep and he saw in a dream the devil, who seized his violin and"                     
[450] "played with master hand the desired sonata. Tartini wrote it out from"                   
[451] "memory when he woke. It has come to us under the name of \\\"The Devil\\'s"              
[452] "Sonata.\\\" But it is very difficult, in regard to such old cases, to"                   
[453] "distinguish between history and legend. We should have auto-observations"                
[454] "of certain authenticity. Now I have not been able to find anything more"                 
[455] "than that of the contemporary English novelist, Stevenson. In a very"                    
[456] "curious essay entitled \\\"A Chapter on Dreams,\\\" this author, who is"                 
[457] "endowed with a rare talent for analysis, explains to us how the most"                    
[458] "original of his stories have been composed or at least sketched in"                      
[459] "dreams. But read the chapter carefully. You will see that at a certain"                  
[460] "time in his life Stevenson had come to be in an habitual psychical state"                
[461] "where it was very hard for him to say whether he was sleeping or waking."                
[462] "That appears to me to be the truth. When the mind creates, I would say"                  
[463] "when it is capable of giving the effort of organization and synthesis"                   
[464] "which is necessary to triumph over a certain difficulty, to solve a"                     
[465] "problem, to produce a living work of the imagination, we are not really"                 
[466] "asleep, or at least that part of ourselves which labors is not the same"                 
[467] "as that which sleeps. We cannot say, then, that it is a dream. In sleep,"                
[468] "properly speaking, in sleep which absorbs our whole personality, it is"                  
[469] "memories and only memories which weave the web of our dreams. But often"                 
[470] "we do not recognize them. They may be very old memories, forgotten"                      
[471] "during waking hours, drawn from the most obscure depths of our past;"                    
[472] "they may be, often are, memories of objects that we have perceived"                      
[473] "distractedly, almost unconsciously, while awake. Or they may be"                         
[474] "fragments of broken memories which have been picked up here and there"                   
[475] "and mingled by chance, composing an incoherent and unrecognizable whole."                
[476] "Before these bizarre assemblages of images which present no plausible"                   
[477] "significance, our intelligence (which is far from surrendering the"                      
[478] "reasoning faculty during sleep, as has been asserted) seeks an"                          
[479] "explanation, tries to fill the lacun\\u00e6. It fills them by calling up other"          
[480] "memories which, presenting themselves often with the same deformations"                  
[481] "and the same incoherences as the preceding, demand in their turn a new"                  
[482] "explanation, and so on indefinitely. But I do not insist upon this point"                
[483] "for the moment. It is sufficient for me to say, in order to answer the"                  
[484] "question which I have propounded, that the formative power of the"                       
[485] "materials furnished to the dream by the different senses, the power"                     
[486] "which converts into precise, determined objects the vague and indistinct"                
[487] "sensations that the dreamer receives from his eyes, his ears, and the"                   
[488] "whole surface and interior of his body, is the memory."                                  
[489] ""                                                                                        
[490] "Memory! In a waking state we have indeed memories which appear and"                      
[491] "disappear, occupying our mind in turn. But they are always memories"                     
[492] "which are closely connected with our present situation, our present"                     
[493] "occupation, our present action. I recall at this moment the book of M."                  
[494] "d\\'Hervey on dreams; that is because I am discussing the subject of"                    
[495] "dreams and this act orients in a certain particular direction the"                       
[496] "activity of my memory. The memories that we evoke while waking, however"                 
[497] "distant they may at first appear to be from the present action, are"                     
[498] "always connected with it in some way. What is the r\\u00f4le of memory in an"            
[499] "animal? It is to recall to him, in any circumstance, the advantageous or"                
[500] "injurious consequences which have formerly arisen in analogous"                          
[501] "circumstances, in order to instruct him as to what he ought to do. In"                   
[502] "man memory is doubtless less the slave of action, but still it sticks to"                
[503] "it. Our memories, at any given moment, form a solid whole, a pyramid, so"                
[504] "to speak, whose point is inserted precisely into our present action. But"                
[505] "behind the memories which are concerned in our occupations and are"                      
[506] "revealed by means of it, there are others, thousands of others, stored"                  
[507] "below the scene illuminated by consciousness. Yes, I believe indeed that"                
[508] "all our past life is there, preserved even to the most infinitesimal"                    
[509] "details, and that we forget nothing, and that all that we have felt,"                    
[510] "perceived, thought, willed, from the first awakening of our"                             
[511] "consciousness, survives indestructibly. But the memories which are"                      
[512] "preserved in these obscure depths are there in the state of invisible"                   
[513] "phantoms. They aspire, perhaps, to the light, but they do not even try"                  
[514] "to rise to it; they know that it is impossible and that I, as a living"                  
[515] "and acting being, have something else to do than to occupy myself with"                  
[516] "them. But suppose that, at a given moment, I become _disinterested_ in"                  
[517] "the present situation, in the present action--in short, in all which"                    
[518] "previously has fixed and guided my memory; suppose, in other words, that"                
[519] "I am asleep. Then these memories, perceiving that I have taken away the"                 
[520] "obstacle, have raised the trapdoor which has kept them beneath the floor"                
[521] "of consciousness, arise from the depths; they rise, they move, they"                     
[522] "perform in the night of unconsciousness a great dance macabre. They rush"                
[523] "together to the door which has been left ajar. They all want to get"                     
[524] "through. But they cannot; there are too many of them. From the"                          
[525] "multitudes which are called, which will be chosen? It is not hard to"                    
[526] "say. Formerly, when I was awake, the memories which forced their way"                    
[527] "were those which could involve claims of relationship with the present"                  
[528] "situation, with what I saw and heard around me. Now it is more vague"                    
[529] "images which occupy my sight, more indecisive sounds which affect my"                    
[530] "ear, more indistinct touches which are distributed over the surface of"                  
[531] "my body, but there are also the more numerous sensations which arise"                    
[532] "from the deepest parts of the organism. So, then, among the phantom"                     
[533] "memories which aspire to fill themselves with color, with sonority, in"                  
[534] "short with materiality, the only ones that succeed are those which can"                  
[535] "assimilate themselves with the color-dust that we perceive, the external"                
[536] "and internal sensations that we catch, etc., and which, besides, respond"                
[537] "to the affective tone of our general sensibility.[1] When this union is"                 
[538] "effected between the memory and the sensation, we have a dream."                         
[539] ""                                                                                        
[540] "In a poetic page of the Enneades, the philosopher Plotinus, interpreter"                 
[541] "and continuator of Plato, explains to us how men come to life. Nature,"                  
[542] "he says, sketches the living bodies, but sketches them only. Left to her"                
[543] "own forces she can never complete the task. On the other hand, souls"                    
[544] "inhabit the world of Ideas. Incapable in themselves of acting, not even"                 
[545] "thinking of action, they float beyond space and beyond time. But, among"                 
[546] "all the bodies, there are some which specially respond by their form to"                 
[547] "the aspirations of some particular souls; and among these souls there"                   
[548] "are those which recognize themselves in some particular body. The body,"                 
[549] "which does not come altogether viable from the hand of nature, rises"                    
[550] "toward the soul which might give it complete life; and the soul, looking"                
[551] "upon the body and believing that it perceives its own image as in a"                     
[552] "mirror, and attracted, fascinated by the image, lets itself fall. It"                    
[553] "falls, and this fall is life. I may compare to these detached souls the"                 
[554] "memories plunged in the obscurity of the unconscious. On the other hand,"                
[555] "our nocturnal sensations resemble these incomplete bodies. The"                          
[556] "sensation is warm, colored, vibrant and almost living, but vague. The"                   
[557] "memory is complete, but airy and lifeless. The sensation wishes to find"                 
[558] "a form on which to mold the vagueness of its contours. The memory would"                 
[559] "obtain matter to fill it, to ballast it, in short to realize it. They"                   
[560] "are drawn toward each other; and the phantom memory, incarnated in the"                  
[561] "sensation which brings to it flesh and blood, becomes a being with a"                    
[562] "life of its own, a dream."                                                               
[563] ""                                                                                        
[564] "The birth of a dream is then no mystery. It resembles the birth of all"                  
[565] "our perceptions. The mechanism of the dream is the same, in general, as"                 
[566] "that of normal perception. When we perceive a real object, what we"                      
[567] "actually see--the sensible matter of our perception--is very little in"                  
[568] "comparison with what our memory adds to it. When you read a book, when"                  
[569] "you look through your newspaper, do you suppose that all the printed"                    
[570] "letters really come into your consciousness? In that case the whole day"                 
[571] "would hardly be long enough for you to read a paper. The truth is that"                  
[572] "you see in each word and even in each member of a phrase only some"                      
[573] "letters or even some characteristic marks, just enough to permit you to"                 
[574] "divine the rest. All of the rest, that you think you see, you really"                    
[575] "give yourself as an hallucination. There are numerous and decisive"                      
[576] "experiments which leave no doubt on this point. I will cite only those"                  
[577] "of Goldscheider and M\\u00fcller. These experimenters wrote or printed some"             
[578] "formulas in common use, \\\"Positively no admission;\\\" \\\"Preface to the"             
[579] "fourth edition,\\\" etc. But they took care to write the words incorrectly,"             
[580] "changing and, above all, omitting letters. These sentences were exposed"                 
[581] "in a darkened room. The person who served as the subject of the"                         
[582] "experiment was placed before them and did not know, of course, what had"                 
[583] "been written. Then the inscription was illuminated by the electric light"                
[584] "for a very short time, too short for the observer to be able to perceive"                
[585] "really all the letters. They began by determining experimentally the"                    
[586] "time necessary for seeing one letter of the alphabet. It was then easy"                  
[587] "to arrange it so that the observer could not perceive more than eight or"                
[588] "ten letters, for example, of the thirty or forty letters composing the"                  
[589] "formula. Usually, however, he read the entire phrase without difficulty."                
[590] "But that is not for us the most instructive point of this experiment."                   
[591] ""                                                                                        
[592] "If the observer is asked what are the letters that he is sure of having"                 
[593] "seen, these may be, of course, the letters really written, but there may"                
[594] "be also absent letters, either letters that we replaced by others or"                    
[595] "that have simply been omitted. Thus an observer will see quite"                          
[596] "distinctly in full light a letter which does not exist, if this letter,"                 
[597] "on account of the general sense, ought to enter into the phrase. The"                    
[598] "characters which have really affected the eye have been utilized only to"                
[599] "serve as an indication to the unconscious memory of the observer. This"                  
[600] "memory, discovering the appropriate remembrance, _i.e._, finding the"                    
[601] "formula to which these characters give a start toward realization,"                      
[602] "projects the remembrance externally in an hallucinatory form. It is"                     
[603] "this remembrance, and not the words themselves, that the observer has"                   
[604] "seen. It is thus demonstrated that rapid reading is in great part a work"                
[605] "of divination, but not of abstract divination. It is an externalization"                 
[606] "of memories which take advantage, to a certain extent, of the partial"                   
[607] "realization that they find here and there in order to completely realize"                
[608] "themselves."                                                                             
[609] ""                                                                                        
[610] "Thus, in the waking state and in the knowledge that we get of the real"                  
[611] "objects which surround us, an operation is continually going on which is"                
[612] "of quite the same nature as that of the dream. We perceive merely a"                     
[613] "sketch of the object. This sketch appeals to the complete memory, and"                   
[614] "this complete memory, which by itself was either unconscious or simply"                  
[615] "in the thought state, profits by the occasion to come out. It is this"                   
[616] "kind of hallucination, inserted and fitted into a real frame, that we"                   
[617] "perceive. It is a shorter process: it is very much quicker done than to"                 
[618] "see the thing itself. Besides, there are many interesting observations"                  
[619] "to be made upon the conduct and attitude of the memory images during"                    
[620] "this operation. It is not necessary to suppose that they are in our"                     
[621] "memory in a state of inert impressions. They are like the steam in a"                    
[622] "boiler, under more or less tension."                                                     
[623] ""                                                                                        
[624] "At the moment when the perceived sketch calls them forth, it is as if"                   
[625] "they were then grouped in families according to their relationship and"                  
[626] "resemblances. There are experiments of M\\u00fcnsterberg, earlier than those"            
[627] "of Goldscheider and M\\u00fcller, which appear to me to confirm this"                    
[628] "hypothesis, although they were made for a very different purpose."                       
[629] "M\\u00fcnsterberg wrote the words correctly; they were, besides, not common"             
[630] "phrases; they were isolated words taken by chance. Here again the word"                  
[631] "was exposed during the time too short for it to be entirely perceived."                  
[632] "Now, while the observer was looking at the written word, some one spoke"                 
[633] "in his ear another word of a very different significance. This is what"                  
[634] "happened: the observer declared that he had seen a word which was not"                   
[635] "the written word, but which resembled it in its general form, and which"                 
[636] "besides recalled, by its meaning, the word which was spoken in his ear."                 
[637] "For example, the word written was \\\"tumult\\\" and the word spoken was"                
[638] "\\\"railroad.\\\" The observer read \\\"tunnel.\\\" The written word was \\\"Trieste\\\""
[639] "and the spoken word was the German \\\"Verzweiflung\\\" (despair). The"                  
[640] "observer read \\\"Trost,\\\" which signifies \\\"consolation.\\\" It is as if the"       
[641] "word \\\"railroad,\\\" pronounced in the ear, wakened, without our knowing it,"          
[642] "hopes of conscious realization in a crowd of memories which have some"                   
[643] "relationship with the idea of \\\"railroad\\\" (car, rail, trip, etc.). But"             
[644] "this is only a hope, and the memory which succeeds in coming into"                       
[645] "consciousness is that which the actually present sensation had already"                  
[646] "begun to realize."                                                                       
[647] ""                                                                                        
[648] "Such is the mechanism of true perception, and such is that of the dream."                
[649] "In both cases there are, on one hand, real impressions made upon the"                    
[650] "organs of sense, and upon the other memories which encase themselves in"                 
[651] "the impression and profit by its vitality to return again to life."                      
[652] ""                                                                                        
[653] "But, then, what is the essential difference between perceiving and"                      
[654] "dreaming? What is sleep? I do not ask, of course, how sleep can be"                      
[655] "explained physiologically. That is a special question, and besides is"                   
[656] "far from being settled. I ask what is sleep psychologically; for our"                    
[657] "mind continues to exercise itself when we are asleep, and it exercises"                  
[658] "itself as we have just seen on elements analogous to those of waking, on"                
[659] "sensations and memories; and also in an analogous manner combines them."                 
[660] "Nevertheless we have on the one hand normal perception, and on the other"                
[661] "the dream. What is the difference, I repeat? What are the psychological"                 
[662] "characteristics of the sleeping state?"                                                  
[663] ""                                                                                        
[664] "We must distrust theories. There are a great many of them on this point."                
[665] "Some say that sleep consists in isolating oneself from the external"                     
[666] "world, in closing the senses to outside things. But we have shown that"                  
[667] "our senses continue to act during sleep, that they provide us with the"                  
[668] "outline, or at least the point of departure, of most of our dreams. Some"                
[669] "say: \\\"To go to sleep is to stop the action of the superior faculties of"              
[670] "the mind,\\\" and they talk of a kind of momentary paralysis of the higher"              
[671] "centers. I do not think that this is much more exact. In a dream we"                     
[672] "become no doubt _indifferent_ to logic, but not _incapable_ of logic."                   
[673] "There are dreams when we reason with correctness and even with subtlety."                
[674] "I might almost say, at the risk of seeming paradoxical, that the mistake"                
[675] "of the dreamer is often in reasoning too much. He would avoid the"                       
[676] "absurdity if he would remain a simple spectator of the procession of"                    
[677] "images which compose his dream. But when he strongly desires to explain"                 
[678] "it, his explanation, intended to bind together incoherent images, can be"                
[679] "nothing more than a bizarre reasoning which verges upon absurdity. I"                    
[680] "recognize, indeed, that our superior intellectual faculties are relaxed"                 
[681] "in sleep, that generally the logic of a dreamer is feeble enough and"                    
[682] "often resembles a mere parody of logic. But one might say as much of all"                
[683] "of our faculties during sleep. It is then not by the abolition of"                       
[684] "reasoning, any more than by the closing of the senses, that we"                          
[685] "characterize dreaming."                                                                  
[686] ""                                                                                        
[687] "Something else is essential. We need something more than theories. We"                   
[688] "need an intimate contact with the facts. One must make the decisive"                     
[689] "experiment upon oneself. It is necessary that on coming out of a dream,"                 
[690] "since we cannot analyze ourselves in the dream itself, we should watch"                  
[691] "the transition from sleeping to waking, follow upon the transition as"                   
[692] "closely as possible, and try to express by words what we experience in"                  
[693] "this passage. This is very difficult, but may be accomplished by forcing"                
[694] "the attention. Permit, then, the writer to take an example from his own"                 
[695] "personal experience, and to tell of a recent dream as well as what was"                  
[696] "accomplished on coming out of the dream."                                                
[697] ""                                                                                        
[698] "Now the dreamer dreamed that he was speaking before an assembly, that he"                
[699] "was making a political speech before a political assembly. Then in the"                  
[700] "midst of the auditorium a murmur rose. The murmur augmented; it became a"                
[701] "muttering. Then it became a roar, a frightful tumult, and finally there"                 
[702] "resounded from all parts timed to a uniform rhythm the cries, \\\"Out!"                  
[703] "Out!\\\" At that moment he wakened. A dog was baying in a neighboring"                   
[704] "garden, and with each one of his \\\"Wow-wows\\\" one of the cries of \\\"Out!"          
[705] "Out!\\\" seemed to be identical. Well, here was the infinitesimal moment"                
[706] "which it is necessary to seize."                                                         
[707] ""                                                                                        
[708] "The waking ego, just reappearing, should turn to the dreaming ego, which"                
[709] "is still there, and, during some instants at least, hold it without"                     
[710] "letting it go. \\\"I have caught you at it! You thought it was a crowd"                  
[711] "shouting and it was a dog barking. Now, I shall not let go of you until"                 
[712] "you tell me just what you were doing!\\\" To which the dreaming ego would"               
[713] "answer, \\\"I was doing nothing; and this is just where you and I differ"                
[714] "from one another. You imagine that in order to hear a dog barking, and"                  
[715] "to know that it is a dog that barks, you have nothing to do. That is a"                  
[716] "great mistake. You accomplish, without suspecting it, a considerable"                    
[717] "effort. You take your entire memory, all your accumulated experience,"                   
[718] "and you bring this formidable mass of memories to converge upon a"                       
[719] "single point, in such a way as to insert exactly in the sounds you heard"                
[720] "that one of your memories which is the most capable of being adapted to"                 
[721] "it. Nay, you must obtain a perfect adherence, for between the memory"                    
[722] "that you evoke and the crude sensation that you perceive there must not"                 
[723] "be the least discrepancy; otherwise you would be just dreaming. This"                    
[724] "adjustment you can only obtain by an effort of the memory and an effort"                 
[725] "of the perception, just as the tailor who is trying on a new coat pulls"                 
[726] "together the pieces of cloth that he adjusts to the shape of your body"                  
[727] "in order to pin them. You exert, then, continually, every moment of the"                 
[728] "day, an enormous effort. Your life in a waking state is a life of labor,"                
[729] "even when you think you are doing nothing, for at every minute you have"                 
[730] "to choose and every minute exclude. You choose among your sensations,"                   
[731] "since you reject from your consciousness a thousand subjective"                          
[732] "sensations which come back in the night when you sleep. You choose, and"                 
[733] "with extreme precision and delicacy, among your memories, since you"                     
[734] "reject all that do not exactly suit your present state. This choice"                     
[735] "which you continually accomplish, this adaptation, ceaselessly renewed,"                 
[736] "is the first and most essential condition of what is called common"                      
[737] "sense. But all this keeps you in a state of uninterrupted tension. You"                  
[738] "do not feel it at the moment, any more than you feel the pressure of the"                
[739] "atmosphere, but it fatigues you in the long run. Common sense is very"                   
[740] "fatiguing."                                                                              
[741] ""                                                                                        
[742] "\\\"So, I repeat, I differ from you precisely in that I do nothing. The"                 
[743] "effort that you give without cessation I simply abstain from giving. In"                 
[744] "place of attaching myself to life, I detach myself from it. Everything"                  
[745] "has become indifferent to me. I have become disinterested in everything."                
[746] "To sleep is to become disinterested. One sleeps to the exact extent to"                  
[747] "which he becomes disinterested. A mother who sleeps by the side of her"                  
[748] "child will not stir at the sound of thunder, but the sigh of the child"                  
[749] "will wake her. Does she really sleep in regard to her child? We do not"                  
[750] "sleep in regard to what continues to interest us."                                       
[751] ""                                                                                        
[752] "\\\"You ask me what it is that I do when I dream? I will tell you what you"              
[753] "do when you are awake. You take me, the me of dreams, me the totality of"                
[754] "your past, and you force me, by making me smaller and smaller, to fit"                   
[755] "into the little circle that you trace around your present action. That"                  
[756] "is what it is to be awake. That is what it is to live the normal"                        
[757] "psychical life. It is to battle. It is to will. As for the dream, have"                  
[758] "you really any need that I should explain it? It is the state into which"                
[759] "you naturally fall when you let yourself go, when you no longer have the"                
[760] "power to concentrate yourself upon a single point, when you have ceased"                 
[761] "to will. What needs much more to be explained is the marvelous mechanism"                
[762] "by which at any moment your will obtains instantly, and almost"                          
[763] "unconsciously, the concentration of all that you have within you upon"                   
[764] "one and the same point, the point that interests you. But to explain"                    
[765] "this is the task of normal psychology, of the psychology of waking, for"                 
[766] "willing and waking are one and the same thing.\\\""                                      
[767] ""                                                                                        
[768] "This is what the dreaming ego would say. And it would tell us a great"                   
[769] "many other things still if we could let it talk freely. But let us sum"                  
[770] "up briefly the essential difference which separates a dream from the"                    
[771] "waking state. In the dream the same faculties are exercised as during"                   
[772] "waking, but they are in a state of tension in the one case, and of"                      
[773] "relaxation in the other. The dream consists of the entire mental life"                   
[774] "minus the tension, the effort and the bodily movement. We perceive"                      
[775] "still, we remember still, we reason still. All this can abound in the"                   
[776] "dream; for abundance, in the domain of the mind, does not mean effort."                  
[777] "What requires an effort is the precision of adjustment. To connect the"                  
[778] "sound of a barking dog with the memory of a crowd that murmurs and"                      
[779] "shouts requires no effort. But in order that this sound should be"                       
[780] "perceived as the barking of a dog, a positive effort must be made. It is"                
[781] "this force that the dreamer lacks. It is by that, and by that alone,"                    
[782] "that he is distinguished from the waking man."                                           
[783] ""                                                                                        
[784] "From this essential difference can be drawn a great many others. We can"                 
[785] "come to understand the chief characteristics of the dream. But I can"                    
[786] "only outline the scheme of this study. It depends especially upon three"                 
[787] "points, which are: the incoherence of dreams, the abolition of the sense"                
[788] "of duration that often appears to be manifested in dreams, and, finally,"                
[789] "the order in which the memories present themselves to the dreamer,"                      
[790] "contending for the sensations present where they are to be embodied."                    
[791] ""                                                                                        
[792] "The incoherence of the dream seems to me easy enough to explain. As it"                  
[793] "is characteristic of the dream not to demand a complete adjustment"                      
[794] "between the memory image and the sensation, but, on the contrary, to"                    
[795] "allow some play between them, very different memories can suit the same"                 
[796] "sensation. For example, there may be in the field of vision a green spot"                
[797] "with white points. This might be a lawn spangled with white flowers. It"                 
[798] "might be a billiard-table with its balls. It might be a host of other"                   
[799] "things besides. These different memory images, all capable of utilizing"                 
[800] "the same sensation, chase after it. Sometimes they attain it, one after"                 
[801] "the other. And so the lawn becomes a billiard-table, and we watch these"                 
[802] "extraordinary transformations. Often it is at the same time, and"                        
[803] "altogether that these memory images join the sensation, and then the"                    
[804] "lawn will be a billiard-table. From this come those absurd dreams where"                 
[805] "an object remains as it is and at the same time becomes something else."                 
[806] "As I have just said, the mind, confronted by these absurd visions, seeks"                
[807] "an explanation and often thereby aggravates the incoherence."                            
[808] ""                                                                                        
[809] "As for the abolition of the sense of time in many of our dreams, that is"                
[810] "another effect of the same cause. In a few seconds a dream can present"                  
[811] "to us a series of events which will occupy, in the waking state, entire"                 
[812] "days. You know the example cited by M. Maury: it has become classic, and"                
[813] "although it has been contested of late, I regard it as probable, because"                
[814] "of the great number of analogous observations that I found scattered"                    
[815] "through the literature of dreams. But this precipitation of the images"                  
[816] "is not at all mysterious. When we are awake we live a life in common"                    
[817] "with our fellows. Our attention to this external and social life is the"                 
[818] "great regulator of the succession of our internal states. It is like"                    
[819] "the balance wheel of a watch, which moderates and cuts into regular"                     
[820] "sections the undivided, almost instantaneous tension of the spring. It"                  
[821] "is this balance wheel which is lacking in the dream. Acceleration is no"                 
[822] "more than abundance a sign of force in the domain of the mind. It is, I"                 
[823] "repeat, the precision of adjustment that requires effort, and this is"                   
[824] "exactly what the dreamer lacks. He is no longer capable of that"                         
[825] "attention to life which is necessary in order that the inner may be"                     
[826] "regulated by the outer, and that the internal duration fit exactly into"                 
[827] "the general duration of things."                                                         
[828] ""                                                                                        
[829] "It remains now to explain how the peculiar relaxation of the mind in the"                
[830] "dream accounts for the preference given by the dreamer to one memory"                    
[831] "image rather than others, equally capable of being inserted into the"                    
[832] "actual sensations. There is a current prejudice to the effect that we"                   
[833] "dream mostly about the events which have especially preoccupied us"                      
[834] "during the day. This is sometimes true. But when the psychological life"                 
[835] "of the waking state thus prolongs itself into sleep, it is because we"                   
[836] "hardly sleep. A sleep filled with dreams of this kind would be a sleep"                  
[837] "from which we come out quite fatigued. In normal sleep our dreams"                       
[838] "concern themselves rather, other things being equal, with the thoughts"                  
[839] "which we have passed through rapidly or upon objects which we have"                      
[840] "perceived almost without paying attention to them. If we dream about"                    
[841] "events of the same day, it is the most insignificant facts, and not the"                 
[842] "most important, which have the best chance of reappearing."                              
[843] ""                                                                                        
[844] "I agree entirely on this point with the observation of W. Robert, of"                    
[845] "Delage and of Freud. I was in the street, I was waiting for a"                           
[846] "street-car, I stood beside the track and did not run the least risk. But"                
[847] "if, at the moment when the street-car passed, the idea of possible"                      
[848] "danger had crossed my mind or even if my body had instinctively recoiled"                
[849] "without my having been conscious of feeling any fear, I might dream that"                
[850] "night that the car had run over my body. I watch at the bedside of an"                   
[851] "invalid whose condition is hopeless. If at any moment, perhaps without"                  
[852] "even being aware of it, I had hoped against hope, I might dream that the"                
[853] "invalid was cured. I should dream of the cure, in any case, more"                        
[854] "probably than that I should dream of the disease. In short, the events"                  
[855] "which reappear by preference in the dream are those of which we have"                    
[856] "thought most distractedly. What is there astonishing about that? The ego"                
[857] "of the dream is an ego that is relaxed; the memories which it gathers"                   
[858] "most readily are the memories of relaxation and distraction, those which"                
[859] "do not bear the mark of effort."                                                         
[860] ""                                                                                        
[861] "It is true that in very profound slumber the law that regulates the"                     
[862] "reappearance of memories may be very different. We know almost nothing"                  
[863] "of this profound slumber. The dreams which fill it are, as a general"                    
[864] "rule, the dreams which we forget. Sometimes, nevertheless, we recover"                   
[865] "something of them. And then it is a very peculiar feeling, strange,"                     
[866] "indescribable, that we experience. It seems to us that we have returned"                 
[867] "from afar in space and afar in time. These are doubtless very old"

[869] "details, with a mood which colors them with that fresh sensation of"                     
[870] "infancy and youth that we seek vainly to revive when awake."

# Project_2 2

#Find word/phase in the given Directory, return value is {document number, line number, and word index}
Find_wordphase <-function(wordphase,path){
  wtmp <-tokens(wordphase)
  wtmp <- unlist(wtmp,use.names = FALSE)
  wordNo <-length(wtmp)
  
  setwd(path)
  getwd()
  SAT<-VCorpus(DirSource(".", ignore.case=TRUE, mode="text"))
  SAT
  documentNo <- NULL
  lineNo <- NULL
  wordInd <- NULL
  sentInd <- NULL
  
  for(i in 1:length(SAT)){
    tmp <-SAT[[i]]$content
    mycorpus <- VCorpus(VectorSource(tmp))
    corpus_frame <- data.frame(text=unlist(sapply(mycorpus, `[`, "content")), stringsAsFactors=F)
    sentences <-chunk_into_sentences(corpus_frame)
    sentences <- removeNumPunct(sentences)
    
    for(j in 1:length(sentences)){
      tmp1 <-tokens(sentences)[j]
      tmp2 <- unlist(tmp1, use.names=FALSE)
      for(m in 1:length(tmp2)){
        count <-0
        n <-1
        while(n<=wordNo){
          if(wtmp[n] == toString(tmp2[m+n-1])){
            count = count+1
          }
          n=n+1
        }
        if(count == wordNo){
          sentInd <-append(sentInd,toString(m))
        }
      }
    }
    
    # Remove punctuation and numbers
    tmp <-removeNumPunct(tmp)
    for(j in 1:length(tmp)){
      tmp1 <-tokens(tmp)[j]
      tmp2 <- unlist(tmp1, use.names=FALSE)
      for(m in 1:length(tmp2)){
        count <-0
        n <-1
        while(n<=wordNo){
          if(wtmp[n] == toString(tmp2[m+n-1])){
            count = count+1
          }
          n=n+1
        }
        if(count == wordNo){
          documentNo <-append(documentNo,toString(i))
          lineNo <-append(lineNo,toString(j))
          wordInd <-append(wordInd,toString(m))
        }
      }
    }
    # Divide each document into sentences
    mycorpus <- VCorpus(VectorSource(tmp))
    corpus_frame <- data.frame(text=unlist(sapply(mycorpus, `[`, "content")), stringsAsFactors=F)
    sentences <-chunk_into_sentences(corpus_frame)
  }
  return(list(paste("Document Number = ", documentNo),
              paste("Line Number = ", lineNo),
              paste("Word Index in line = ", wordInd),
              paste("Word Index in sentence = ", sentInd)))
}
